  "opinion": "As a woman with four children who's worked in the trades since I was 16, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can silence potential in STEM fields. When I was growing up, my parents—both from vocational backgrounds—taught me that engineering and technology were for 'men' and 'hard workers,' not for girls like me. Back in the 90s, when I first got my electrician's license, I remember feeling nervous about being the only woman in the shop who wasn't wearing a tool belt. The stereotype that women aren't good at math or problem-solving made me doubt myself even when I could fix a circuit in seconds. But what's really worrying is how this mindset affects our kids today. My sons, who are now in high school, are taught that STEM is 'for boys' by their teachers and peers. I've volunteered with after-school programs where I see kids—especially girls—shying away from math because they think it's 'not for them.' Stereotype threat isn't just a theory; it's real, and it's costing us talented people who could change the world. We should address it by starting in schools, where teachers can normalize girls in engineering classes and show them that women have always been innovators. For example, when my daughter's school introduced a robotics club, I pushed for more female mentors to join. It worked—now she's leading the team. Addressing stereotype threat isn't about changing the system overnight; it's about small, consistent efforts that build confidence. As a working mother who's seen the impact of these biases on my own children, I believe we can turn this around by focusing on real-world examples and creating safe spaces where everyone feels they belong.",
